'''Sapere aude''' is a [[Latin language|Latin]] phrase meaning "Dare to know" or "Dare to be wise", or sometimes translated as "Have courage to use your own reason". Most famously, it is found in [[Immanuel Kant]]'s essay "[[What Is Enlightenment?]]". The original use seems to be in [[Epistle]] II of [[Horace]]'s [[Epistularum liber primus]] [http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/horace/epist1.shtml], line 40: ''Dimidium facti qui coepit habet: sapere aude'' ("He who has begun is half done: dare to know!"). 

It is a frequently used [[motto]]. Some users of the motto are listed below.

